{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493363"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1301"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1301"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.06,0.05,0.74,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43663"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1301"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28670"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44340"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43663"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents with a one-week history of night sweats, accompanied by a sore throat. He denies any weight loss, daytime fever, anorexia, loss of appetite, cough, dyspnoea, or abdominal symptoms. He has just returned from a trip to Brazil. He reports being compliant with recommendations to use insect repellent and wearing protective clothing that reduced the amount of exposed skin. He did not participate in any sexual activity\u00a0while\u00a0on his trip and did not get any tattoos. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 130/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. He is not jaundiced. There is lymphadenopathy of the anterior chain bilaterally. His left tonsil is covered in white exudate. His chest is clear on auscultation. There is fullness in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Human immunodeficiency virus","Dengue fever","Malaria","Epstein Barr virus","Streptococcal pharyngitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in the context of acute onset of night sweats, sore throat, objective fever, cervical lymphadenopathy and tonsillitis with splenomegaly, as inferred by the left upper quadrant fullness.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Estreptococcal pharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable differential diagnosis for sore throat with objective fever and cervical lymphadenopathy, it is unlikely to manifest with splenomegaly and night sweats.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn context of his recent travel to Brazil,\u003Cstrong\u003E dengue fever\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emalaria\u003C/strong\u003E are important diagnoses to consider and exclude, as these vector-borne diseases are endemic in this region of the world. Both are made less likely in context of the patient reporting he was compliant with recommendations to use insect repellent and wearing protective clothing that reduced the amount of exposed skin, although it is not impossible to context these diseases in spite of these measures. However, in the case of dengue fever, this diagnosis is less likely in the absence of myalgias, daytime fever and rash, and it is unlikely to account for his splenomegaly and tonsillitis. Regarding malaria, this too is less likely in the absence of myalgias, anorexia and abdominal symptoms. Whilst malaria might explain his splenomegaly, it is unlikely to account for his tonsillitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus (HIV) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a differential diagnosis that must be considered, especially when a patient is a returned traveller and might have participated in high-risk activities. Whilst acute HIV infection might present with night sweats, objective fever, sore throat, splenomegaly and cervical lymphadenopathy, the patient denies any sexual activity and did not get a tattoo, both of which are possible routes of HIV transmission. Further, this diagnosis is unlikely to present with unilateral exudate and often, the patient will experience a seroconversion rash and abdominal symptoms like\u00a0diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Epstein Barr virus is characterised by acute onset of night sweats, sore throat, objective fever, cervical lymphadenopathy and tonsillitis with splenomegaly."],"references":["Womack J, Jimenez M. Common Questions About Infectious Mononucleosis. Am Fam Physician 2015; 91:372-76. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25822555/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28670"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1301"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28670"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-25T12:55:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-25T12:55:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1301"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43663"}}},"met